### Figure 2: Occupation Analysis
![Job Analysis](file:///c:/Users/emir/Desktop/403/job_analysis.png)
*Caption: Students and retirees show significantly higher subscription rates compared to working professionals.*

### Figure 3: Education Level Impact
![Education Analysis](file:///c:/Users/emir/Desktop/403/education_analysis.png)
*Caption: Paradoxically, lower education levels correlate with higher subscription rates.*

### Figure 4: Marital Status Analysis
![Marital Analysis](file:///c:/Users/emir/Desktop/403/marital_analysis.png)
*Caption: Single customers demonstrate highest subscription propensity.*

### Figure 5: Campaign Characteristics
![Campaign Analysis](file:///c:/Users/emir/Desktop/403/campaign_analysis.png)
*Caption: Call duration emerges as strongest predictor; optimal contact frequency is 1-2 attempts.*

### Figure 6: Economic Indicators
![Economic Analysis](file:///c:/Users/emir/Desktop/403/economic_analysis.png)
*Caption: Strong correlation between Euribor3m and other economic indicators; lower rates correlate with higher subscriptions.*

### Figure 7: Cross-Analysis - Marital Status × Age
![Cross Analysis Marital Age](file:///c:/Users/emir/Desktop/403/cross_analysis_marital_age.png)
*Caption: Single young and divorced senior segments show highest conversion combinations.*

### Figure 8: Cross-Analysis - Occupation × Education × Age
![Cross Analysis Job Education Age](file:///c:/Users/emir/Desktop/403/cross_analysis_job_edu_age.png)
